Maverick Boys had a great week!

At the St. Pats Cross Country Invitational held on 09/03/2020, Isaac Goosey placed 8th for the Junior High Boys. In the high school boys division we had three medalists, Colin Rooney 2nd, Rylin Johns 10th and Jared Trimble 12th. The boys also placed second as a team!

Last night, the Maverick football traveled and made Oveton a "no fly zone", grounding the Eagles 42-20.

Lastly, wish the the Maverick Cross Country team luck today at Cozad.

Go Mavericks!

post_text:
The Stapleton Education Association is once again collecting $30 from each teacher in exchange for wearing jeans on Fridays. The thirty dollars goes into a scholarship fund to award scholarships to Stapleton students majoring in education. The association will award up to three scholarships of $300 each. In the past few years, this scholarship has received matching funds and has turned into a $600 scholarship. Scholarship recipients are selected using an interview process. We encourage any seniors planning on majoring in education to participate in the interview.

Mrs. Monson, elementary special education teacher, poses in her jeans after donating $30 to the Stapleton Education Association scholarship fund.

post_text:
Class Dojo is the communication tool that the elementary teachers have chosen to utilize for grades preschool through fifth grade. Parents may have already received emails or texts about setting up Class Dojo. If any parents are needing help, feel free to contact the teacher or the community liaison, Lacy Kinderknecht. They would be more than willing to help you download the app or with any of the set-up. There is also a helpful video found on YouTube: https://youtu.be/vZWYMcDuhus.

Our goal is to reach 100% of our parents. Class Dojo is a great communication tool for parents and teachers to message one-on-one, teachers can post any announcements on the Class Story, share pictures, monitor student behavior by giving or taking away points, and highlight student learning in their individual portfolios.

Logan County Library
August 12 at 12:00 PM ·

WIN A KINDLE!!! It's the Nebraska August Reading Challenge! All ages are welcome to join in!

Here's how:
1. Download the Reading Zone app on your device or go to https://app.readerzone.com/signup to sign up via a computer!
2. Once signed in it will ask you to select a program, you will need to enter the code NEB1K and select the "August Reading Challenge" in the drop down (see comments for that screen shot if needed, may look different on phone or tablet).
3. Log your reading minutes each day through August!

Please be sure to fill in your mailing address and details so they can mail you stickers and a free kindle if you win the drawing!

The elementary staff met this summer to choose one communication tool to use throughout the elementary, which will be Class Dojo! Our teachers have done a great job communicating with parents, but have used multiple communication tools like ClassTag, Facebook groups, and Class Dojo. To make it easier on the families that have more than one child in elementary school, parents will use just one communication tool to stay connected with each class. Parents may start receiving invitations to join Class Dojo at any time. We look forward to having one system to communicate with you this school year!

You can download the app on any smartphone.

Public Notice
Non-public Consultation Meeting
Stapleton Public Schools - Logan District #57-0501
Tuesday, June 23, 2020

On June 23, 2020 at 8:30 a.m., a meeting conducted by Stapleton Public Schools will take place at the school library. The purpose of the meeting will be to provide an opportunity for parents and representatives of nonpublic schools to participate in the development of a plan for providing special education services to children with disabilities who attend nonpublic schools and home schools which are within the Stapleton school district for the 2020-2021 school year. Parents of a home-schooled child or a child attending a nonpublic school who has been or may be identified with a disability and attend a nonpublic school within the boundaries of Stapleton Public Schools, are urged to attend. If you have further questions pertaining to this meeting, please contact Howard Gaffney, Superintendent, at 308-636-2252.

post_text:
Check out this website shared with us: https://cehs.unl.edu/comingtogetherforwellness/

Important highlights of the site:

Easy to sign up for 30 min free consult with a therapist.

Facebook group for people to support and encourage one another https://www.facebook.com/groups/532767604340716/ (70 people signed up in the first 12 hours).

WhatsApp group chat. Some felt they were more likely to text messages of encouragement – WhatsApp is especially important for our immigrant/refugee populations.

Phone and Zoom support group times during the week (for now Tuesday, Thursday and Saturday). The purpose is for social support and connection.

Fun tips of the day: Today’s is Pirate hour – during a specific hour of the day everyone has to talk with a pirate accent.

Podcast for support and ideas about strengthening individuals and families. First Podcast going up today, I hope.

Simple and easy tips and resources so people don’t have to sift through mountains of info.

There has been some confusion regarding the last Blackboard message that was sent on Wednesday, April 15. The school’s intent is to create a consistent delivery system that will reduce parent trips to school. It began with the school getting computers and locker items to students. Lower elementary instructors are now sending learning packets to students.

The primary purpose of the Blackboard message was to alert parents to the fact that the delivery date was changed from Thursday to Friday. Instructors or the school system will let students and parents know if there are materials that need to be picked up If you have not heard from us you do NOT need to come to the school on Friday.

Mr. Paben is coordinating the delivery system. You may contact him at his email address, jeff.paben@stapletonschools.org. The system works both ways. If you need something from school let Mr. Paben know prior to the delivery date. In addition, if you don't live in North Platte but want to pick up student materials email Mr. Paben.

post_text:
SPS is very excited to announce Ms. Weinman as an Upper Elementary Teacher! Please join us in welcoming her to our wonderful community!

"I grew up and went to school in Arnold, NE and graduated in 2003. I then went to North Platte Community College on a volleyball scholarship and graduated with my Associates degree in 2005 before finishing my teaching degree at UNL in December 2007. I was hired right away and went to Grand Island Public Schools where I taught 5th grade and earned my Master's Degree as a Reading Specialist in 2012 while teaching. Since then I have continued to take online classes over various teaching components through Morningside College. I am very excited to begin teaching in Stapleton because of the community's value of education and the school's reputation."

Due to the Covid-19 Pandemic of 2020, Canvas is the Learning Management System that will be utilized by the 7-12 staff at Stapleton Public Schools. This allows parents/students to access the necessary tools and resources toward the continuity of their child(ren)'s education. Each student has access to an account to see course calendars, download or complete digital papers and assignments, engage in secure class discussions with their classmates, etc. Parents can become an “Observer” of their child’s account to view what is going on with their child’s account.

Click on this link for instructions:
https://docs.google.com/document/d/1l10e1auxW_cJQDdeQ6Brt-gcnKjtTEnCOuMulsBUXVY/edit?usp=sharing

We have some new staff hired for next fall! While we are sad to lose Miss Knust, we are excited to welcome Ms. Nichols as our new kindergarten teacher. Everyone, please give her a warm Stapleton welcome!

"My name is Dawnae Nichols and I grew up on a farm outside of Miller, Nebraska. I graduated from Sumner-Eddyville-Miller high school in 2016. Then I continued my education at Chadron State College, majoring in Elementary Education (K-8) and completing my student teaching at Hitchcock County Elementary. In December 2019, I graduated from college and became a substitute teacher for the Hitchcock County school district. I wanted to start my teaching career in Stapleton because it is a small community that reminds me of home. During my initial visit I felt welcomed in both the school and the community."

The number of confirmed COVID-19 cases has moved to 12 in the West Central Health District. Logan county and Stapleton Public Schools are part of this district. For this reason, Governor Pete Rickets has ordered Directed Health Measures. This means that schools must be closed through May 31 and extracurricular activities are canceled.

You may still come to the school today to pick up packets for lower elementary and personal belongs for all classes.

Drive along the street by the northwest door and you items will be brought out to you. Please stay in your cars, we cannot allow any additional people in the building.

Distribution to North Platte has been postponed to Monday, April 6 from 5:00 PM to 6:30 PM at Cody Park due to weather.

Stay safe and stay healthy!!!

#wereinthistogether

Computers Available for Family Use:

Mr. Kloke, Mrs. Hauser, and Mr. Paben have organized computers. Our goal is for each family to have a computer to use either their own or one provided by the school. This is how we will communicate with students and share learning activities.

Instructors will be ready to distribute them to families on Thursday, March 26. Please pull up to the northwest exit between the Library and 2nd Grade room between 11:00 a.m and 4:00 pm. If these times do not work please contact the school and make arrangements for a time that does works for you.

For safety reasons, we do not want students in the building. Instructors will watch for your vehicle and they will bring the computer and charge cord to your car. You will not even have to get out of your vehicle. Additional information regarding learning activities will be shared soon.

Thank you for your patience as we work together to figure this out!

Logan County Library
March 25 at 2:05 PM ·

We want to remind our community of the great service we offer that gives you access to thousands of books without having to leave your home!

This is a FREE service offered to our community and surrounding community members, and we highly encourage school students to take advantage of Overdrive during these trying times.

1. HOW TO SIGN UP? Message us on Facebook and we will get you your Overdrive number. Our Library is currently closed until our commissioners deem it safe to be open to the public but we are still offering this service!

2. HOW DO I USE? Visit Overdrive with app or url provided below, search for Logan County Library, enter library card number we provided, and sign in to browse thousands of books that you can read from your mobile devices! It’s that easy!

Apps to access Overdrive:
Newer devices download app: “Libby, by Overdrive” (more Kindle friendly)

Dated devices download app: “Overdrive: eBooks & audiobooks”

To use from your computer go to:
https://nebraska.overdrive.com/

The below email was sent to the school:

All,



The NSAA is aware of the fluidity of COVID-19 and the potential impact hosting statewide events could have regarding the on-going public health threat. Many of our member schools are making decisions in the best interest of their student participants, coaches and communities. The NSAA is regretfully suspending district and state speech contests until further notice.



This is an unprecedented event. The NSAA Board of Directors and staff understand the hardship this has created for our membership. The NSAA will use this time to evaluate potential alternatives and the next steps for moving forward.



Sincerely,



Jeff Stauss

Assistant Director

Nebraska School Activities Association

Test your geography knowledge:

1. Grand Traverse Bay borders the Lower Peninsula of which state - South Dakota or Michigan?

2. Estancias is the term for large cattle ranches in the second largest country by area in South America. Name this country.

This Wednesday, January 15th, at 1:30 PM, ten finalists will be competing in the School Geography Bee. Good luck to our finalists!

Answers: 1. Michigan, 2. Argentina

On Friday, the elementary student council hosted the second elementary celebration. Here are some highlights:

1. All of the elementary students have been caught being good at least once, and many have been caught being good multiple times!

2. Students who have been caught being good get their slip entered for Minute to Win It challenges and six get drawn to eat with Mr. Gaffney.

3. Nancy Lashley was our guest speaker who announced the winners of the veterans essays, and she taught the students how to act during a parade when the flag goes by.

We are going to continue to learn about how static electricity works and what it effects!
